  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Multiple offers tend to happen in a specific set of circumstances: a rising market, a well-presented property in a suburb where stock is tight, or a campaign that generates early momentum and brings several genuinely interested buyers to the table at the same time. When it happens, the natural instinct for sellers is to try to push everyone for their absolute best price. That instinct is right in principle, but the execution matters a great deal. Handled poorly, a multiple-offer situation can end up with fewer buyers than you started with.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Your legal position in Queensland</h2>
      <p>As a seller in Queensland, you are not obligated to accept any offer. You may accept, reject, or counter any offer at your absolute discretion until contracts are exchanged. You are also not required to disclose to any buyer that competing offers exist, or to reveal the terms of any offer you have received. This gives you genuine flexibility in how you manage the process.</p>

      <p>The one absolute rule: you cannot accept two contracts simultaneously. Only one contract can be live at a time in Queensland. If you sign a contract with Buyer A, you cannot simultaneously sign one with Buyer B as a backup. The correct approach is to either accept one offer and let the others lapse, or work through the process properly before signing anything. Your agent and conveyancer should both be across this.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The three main approaches agents use</h2>
      <p>When multiple offers arrive, your agent will typically recommend one of three approaches depending on the number of buyers, the spread between offers, and your own timeline.</p>

      <p>The first is a highest-and-best round. All buyers are informed that competing offers exist and invited to submit their best offer by a set deadline. This approach is transparent, gives every buyer a fair opportunity to put their best foot forward, and often produces a meaningful uplift in the final number. The risk is that some buyers, particularly those who are already at their limit, may choose to withdraw rather than participate in what feels like an auction process. A bird-in-hand consideration applies: a strong unconditional offer already on the table is worth more than the possibility of a higher one that may not materialise.</p>

      <p>The second approach is sequential negotiation. The agent works through the buyers one at a time, starting with whoever has submitted the strongest initial offer, and negotiates to a conclusion before engaging the next. This is less transparent but keeps each negotiation contained and reduces the risk of losing all buyers simultaneously. It works best when one offer is clearly stronger than the others or when buyer numbers are small.</p>

      <p>The third is an informal auction, where buyers are invited to submit offers with the understanding that the seller will select the most attractive. This sits somewhere between the two approaches and suits situations where there are several genuinely competitive buyers and the seller wants to maintain optionality without running a formal auction process.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What makes an offer strong beyond the price</h2>
      <p>Price is the most visible component of an offer but not always the deciding factor. In a multiple-offer situation, the terms can matter as much as the number. An unconditional offer carries significant weight. A buyer who has arranged finance pre-approval, conducted their building and pest inspection before making an offer, and submitted without a finance clause is offering genuine certainty. That certainty has real value, particularly if you are selling into a purchase on the other side and need confidence about your own settlement.</p>

      <p>Settlement timing is another factor that sellers often underestimate. If you need a longer settlement to coordinate your own move or purchase, a buyer offering a 90-day settlement at a slightly lower price may be worth more to you in practical terms than a buyer offering a higher price with a 30-day clause. Conversely, if you need a fast settlement, the buyer who can move quickly has a meaningful advantage regardless of where the price sits relative to their competitors.</p>

      <p>Deposit size also signals buyer commitment. A larger deposit represents a higher financial cost to the buyer if they default, which reduces the practical risk of a late fall-through. On a high-value property, the difference between a 5% and a 10% deposit matters.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What sellers should not do</h2>
      <p>There are a few specific mistakes to avoid. Do not mislead buyers about the existence or strength of competing offers. If you tell a buyer there is a higher offer on the table when there is not, you create legal risk for your agent and reputational risk for yourself. Buyers talk, and the Brisbane inner-east market is smaller than it appears.</p>

      <p>Do not drag out the process. Buyers who are serious have other options. If a multiple-offer situation is not resolved efficiently, the buyers at the top of your list will move to another property. The goal is to maximise the outcome for the best offer that is actually achievable, not to hold out indefinitely for a number that may never arrive.</p>

      <p>Finally, do not make the decision based purely on price when the terms of a lower offer represent meaningfully better certainty. A sale that proceeds smoothly to settlement is worth more than a higher-priced sale that falls over two weeks before you are due to move.</p>

